WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.980 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.980 --> 00:00:08.466 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:08.466 --> 00:00:24.279 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.279 --> 00:00:26.070 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:26.070 --> 00:00:29.250 align:middle line:10%
I'm George Noory, physicist and
licensed professional engineer.

00:00:29.250 --> 00:00:30.750 align:middle line:90%
Dr. Tom Valone with us.

00:00:30.750 --> 00:00:33.360 align:middle line:10%
He has a PhD in
general engineering

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:36.480 align:middle line:10%
and a masters in physics,
president and founder

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:39.000 align:middle line:10%
of the Integrity
Research Institute,

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:42.030 align:middle line:10%
and author of several books,
including "Zero Point Energy."

00:00:42.030 --> 00:00:43.740 align:middle line:90%
Tom, welcome to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:44.160 align:middle line:90%
>>TOM VALONE: Thank you.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:44.410 align:middle line:90%
Glad to be here.

00:00:44.410 --> 00:00:45.580 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What's new with you?

00:00:45.580 --> 00:00:46.621 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Oh my goodness.

00:00:46.621 --> 00:00:49.050 align:middle line:10%
The biggest thing I
feel is the discovery

00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:52.650 align:middle line:10%
of the new development
on climate change, which

00:00:52.650 --> 00:00:59.700 align:middle line:10%
was predicted over 10 years
ago by Dr. Jim Hansen, MIT

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:01.740 align:middle line:10%
climatologist, probably
the world's most famous

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:02.580 align:middle line:10%
climatologist.

00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:04.825 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is he controversial?

00:01:04.825 --> 00:01:05.700 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:08.040 align:middle line:10%
The Bush administration
tried to censor him.

00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:10.230 align:middle line:10%
And he was persecuted
during the years

00:01:10.230 --> 00:01:14.160 align:middle line:10%
that that administration
had the White House.

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:17.280 align:middle line:84%
No words like that in
any government report.

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:20.130 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tom, when we talk
about climate change, what

00:01:20.130 --> 00:01:21.460 align:middle line:90%
are we talking about?

00:01:21.460 --> 00:01:23.970 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well, the first graph
is basically a slide showing

00:01:23.970 --> 00:01:27.300 align:middle line:84%
his 400,000-year
history of the Earth.

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:31.110 align:middle line:84%
And what he did beyond what
Noah did is not only showing

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:34.890 align:middle line:84%
the carbon dioxide
change over those years--

00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:37.590 align:middle line:84%
you can see several ice
ages as a result of this--

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:41.160 align:middle line:84%
but he also superimposed the
temperature and sea level

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:44.076 align:middle line:84%
graphs with the maximum
and minimum matched up.

00:01:44.076 --> 00:01:46.200 align:middle line:84%
And all of a sudden, you
see they track each other.

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:48.180 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right, we'll get
into all this in just a second.

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:49.680 align:middle line:84%
Tell us a little
bit more about you.

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:51.960 align:middle line:84%
How'd you get involved
in studying all this?

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:53.700 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well, years
ago, I was involved

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:55.830 align:middle line:90%
in pursuing free energy.

00:01:55.830 --> 00:01:58.680 align:middle line:84%
And in 1980, I basically
went to Germany

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:01.650 align:middle line:84%
for a conference on
gravity field energy.

00:02:01.650 --> 00:02:04.110 align:middle line:84%
And from then on, I
was actually involved

00:02:04.110 --> 00:02:08.220 align:middle line:84%
in the polar generator, thinking
that was a free energy device.

00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:10.889 align:middle line:84%
I convinced my professor at
the University of Buffalo

00:02:10.889 --> 00:02:13.620 align:middle line:84%
to let me do it as a
master's project in physics.

00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:15.960 align:middle line:90%
And then I became a celebrity.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:17.670 align:middle line:84%
Every year I was
going to conferences

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:20.760 align:middle line:84%
and talking about free energy
and was even a consultant

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:24.240 align:middle line:84%
for the "Free Energy,
Race to Zero Point" video.

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:26.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, when you
talk about free energy,

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:29.700 align:middle line:84%
now to me that means we're
not getting electrical bills

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:31.320 align:middle line:90%
from our electric company.

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:32.340 align:middle line:90%
Is that what you mean?

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:33.310 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Of course.

00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:35.850 align:middle line:84%
It's a one-time investment
in some type of device.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:37.770 align:middle line:84%
And that's some
of the information

00:02:37.770 --> 00:02:42.510 align:middle line:84%
we'll be sharing today that
actually involves a device that

00:02:42.510 --> 00:02:46.410 align:middle line:84%
then produces energy,
electrical energy,

00:02:46.410 --> 00:02:47.994 align:middle line:90%
for as long as the device works.

00:02:47.994 --> 00:02:49.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They're
not going to want

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:51.480 align:middle line:90%
us to have that, Tom, are they?

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:53.520 align:middle line:90%
It's free.

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:56.430 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well, I think
it's our manifest destiny,

00:02:56.430 --> 00:02:58.590 align:middle line:84%
as they called it years
ago when we were trying

00:02:58.590 --> 00:03:00.580 align:middle line:90%
to get to the West coast.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:02.310 align:middle line:90%
Hey, we used to have free water.

00:03:02.310 --> 00:03:03.500 align:middle line:90%
We used to have free air.

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:04.300 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:03:04.300 --> 00:03:05.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They found a
way to make money on it.

00:03:05.700 --> 00:03:06.640 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: That's
right, that's right.

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:08.490 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And here we go again.

00:03:08.490 --> 00:03:12.210 align:middle line:90%
Climate change is controversial.

00:03:12.210 --> 00:03:14.310 align:middle line:84%
People on different
ends of the spectrum

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:17.400 align:middle line:84%
have their own specific
views on whether it's

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:22.330 align:middle line:84%
man-made or natural, maybe
a combination of both.

00:03:22.330 --> 00:03:24.850 align:middle line:90%
But why is it so controversial?

00:03:24.850 --> 00:03:27.990 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well, the controversy
is basically the same paradigm

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:30.240 align:middle line:84%
shift that Thomas
Kuhn talked about

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:34.590 align:middle line:84%
in the scientific revolutions
book, "Structure of Scientific

00:03:34.590 --> 00:03:35.420 align:middle line:90%
Revolutions."

00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:37.380 align:middle line:84%
You see it repeated
over and over again.

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:40.200 align:middle line:84%
Anything analogous,
it tends to be denied.

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:41.700 align:middle line:90%
That's the human reaction.

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:42.500 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:45.000 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: And Kuhn mapped
that down to the point

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:46.540 align:middle line:84%
where unless a
theory is developed

00:03:46.540 --> 00:03:50.019 align:middle line:84%
that's very convincing, people
are still going to dismiss it.

00:03:50.019 --> 00:03:52.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now before we get into
the graphics from Jim Hansen,

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:53.420 align:middle line:90%
tell us about him.

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:54.420 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Oh, of course.

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:58.590 align:middle line:84%
Jim Hansen is a soft-spoken,
wonderful genius

00:03:58.590 --> 00:04:00.690 align:middle line:84%
who's co-authored
amazing journal

00:04:00.690 --> 00:04:02.220 align:middle line:90%
articles on climate change.

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:05.610 align:middle line:84%
But he hasn't reached the
audience that's most important.

00:04:05.610 --> 00:04:07.140 align:middle line:90%
And that is the public.

00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:08.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why not?

00:04:08.190 --> 00:04:11.220 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well, scientists
are accused of this everywhere

00:04:11.220 --> 00:04:14.640 align:middle line:84%
in the world, including,
as people might remember,

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:18.000 align:middle line:84%
in Greece where scientists
were put in jail,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.630 align:middle line:84%
geologists specifically, for
publishing their articles

00:04:21.630 --> 00:04:24.090 align:middle line:84%
on the coming earthquake
that they had predicted

00:04:24.090 --> 00:04:27.060 align:middle line:84%
and didn't do enough advertising
to convince the public

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:28.230 align:middle line:90%
to go seek shelter.

00:04:28.230 --> 00:04:29.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So they
blamed them for it.

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:30.163 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Of course.

00:04:30.163 --> 00:04:31.710 align:middle line:84%
And they put them
in jail in Greece.

00:04:31.710 --> 00:04:33.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Sheesh,
are you kidding me?

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:35.329 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: I said, hey,
that's what it should be,

00:04:35.329 --> 00:04:37.840 align:middle line:84%
because scientists should
be their own spokesperson

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:45.180 align:middle line:84%
and announcers for the type
of important information

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:47.100 align:middle line:90%
that they're presenting.

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:49.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Whose fault
was that, then?

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:51.870 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it was the
fault of the scientists

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:53.610 align:middle line:90%
and the climatologists.

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:55.680 align:middle line:84%
It could have been
the media in Greece

00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:56.764 align:middle line:90%
that didn't pick up on it.

00:04:56.764 --> 00:04:58.263 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Thank you
for saying that,

00:04:58.263 --> 00:04:59.470 align:middle line:90%
because it wasn't my words.

00:04:59.470 --> 00:05:00.270 align:middle line:90%
It was yours.

00:05:00.270 --> 00:05:04.500 align:middle line:84%
And hey, the media obviously
is being blamed left and right

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:06.580 align:middle line:90%
for lots of different reasons.

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:09.030 align:middle line:84%
But in general, we
need more science

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:11.190 align:middle line:90%
to be translated by the media.

00:05:11.190 --> 00:05:13.830 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Dr. Jim Hansen
out at Columbia University

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:15.380 align:middle line:90%
created what he has.

00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:17.214 align:middle line:90%
It's called the climate graph.

00:05:17.214 --> 00:05:18.630 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at some
of these graphs

00:05:18.630 --> 00:05:20.910 align:middle line:84%
and you explain to
us, if you would, Tom,

00:05:20.910 --> 00:05:22.150 align:middle line:90%
what we're looking at here.

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:23.290 align:middle line:90%
So what is this?

00:05:23.290 --> 00:05:24.831 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well, this
is the first one

00:05:24.831 --> 00:05:28.480 align:middle line:84%
that he published in an
obscure journal called "MIT's

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:31.140 align:middle line:90%
Technology Review," 2006.

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:35.860 align:middle line:84%
And when I study this graph,
400,000 years of ice age up

00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:41.290 align:middle line:84%
and down temperature, CO2,
and sea level superimposed

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:44.020 align:middle line:84%
so you can see they
actually overlap, to me this

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:46.840 align:middle line:84%
is astonishing, because
no one, I think,

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:50.440 align:middle line:84%
even scientists, have a
formula or an understanding

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:52.830 align:middle line:84%
of why the three of
them are correlated.

00:05:52.830 --> 00:05:56.680 align:middle line:84%
They're diverse parts of
the biosphere, of Gaia.

00:05:56.680 --> 00:06:00.610 align:middle line:10%
And what's astonishing, as Al
Gore does in the "Inconvenient

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:03.250 align:middle line:10%
Truth" movie, all of a sudden
you see at the very end,

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:06.130 align:middle line:10%
at this time in
2006, it went way up

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:08.700 align:middle line:10%
to 377 parts per million.

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:12.220 align:middle line:10%
Well, the maximum that you see
across the half million years

00:06:12.220 --> 00:06:14.180 align:middle line:10%
is only 290 parts per million.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:18.490 align:middle line:84%
It's varied between 200
and 300 parts per million

00:06:18.490 --> 00:06:19.900 align:middle line:90%
for a half million years.

00:06:19.900 --> 00:06:24.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, humans or somebody is
pushing that CO2 up to now 408.

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:25.780 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Or somebody.

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:26.425 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Yeah, or somebody.

00:06:26.425 --> 00:06:26.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Or someone.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:28.210 align:middle line:10%
>>VALONE: So as you go
to the second graph--

00:06:28.210 --> 00:06:28.900 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Let's lay it out.

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:30.670 align:middle line:10%
Let's go to the second
one and see what we have.

00:06:30.670 --> 00:06:32.294 align:middle line:10%
>>VALONE: What I did
is I annotated it,

00:06:32.294 --> 00:06:35.560 align:middle line:10%
because there was a table
next to that graph that

00:06:35.560 --> 00:06:37.450 align:middle line:10%
at least showed the numbers.

00:06:37.450 --> 00:06:39.096 align:middle line:90%
And I chided Jim.

00:06:39.096 --> 00:06:40.220 align:middle line:90%
I talked to him about this.

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:42.070 align:middle line:84%
I said, this is
exactly what people

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:44.770 align:middle line:84%
need to understand the
graph that you published,

00:06:44.770 --> 00:06:47.270 align:middle line:84%
because at the bottom
here is my key.

00:06:47.270 --> 00:06:49.600 align:middle line:84%
10 parts per million equal
a half degree C equal

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:51.847 align:middle line:90%
10 meters of sea level rise.

00:06:51.847 --> 00:06:53.680 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's forget about
the sea level rise,

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:56.590 align:middle line:84%
because it takes a millennium
or more for that to happen.

00:06:56.590 --> 00:06:57.610 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's very slow.

00:06:57.610 --> 00:06:58.640 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Very slow.

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:02.300 align:middle line:84%
So the one I'm concentrating
on is the temperature.

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:04.190 align:middle line:10%
And the temperature you see--

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:06.550 align:middle line:10%
you can even say 20 parts per
million equal one degree--

00:07:06.550 --> 00:07:09.330 align:middle line:10%


00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:11.680 align:middle line:10%
it's calibrated so you
can actually predict,

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:15.700 align:middle line:10%
as I did 10 years ago, what
the future temperature change

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:18.650 align:middle line:10%
should be within the century.

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:20.920 align:middle line:84%
And as you can see, I'm
annotating five degrees

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:25.220 align:middle line:84%
C at that time just due to
the approximately 400 parts

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:26.020 align:middle line:90%
per million--

00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:27.430 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is that high?

00:07:27.430 --> 00:07:28.520 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Five degrees C?

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:28.670 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:07:28.670 --> 00:07:29.380 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:30.340 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is.

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:33.350 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Nat Geo has a video
saying one or two degrees

00:07:33.350 --> 00:07:34.150 align:middle line:90%
is tolerable.

00:07:34.150 --> 00:07:36.100 align:middle line:84%
But as you get to
three, four, and five,

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:39.070 align:middle line:84%
we get desertification
of the Midwest.

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:42.430 align:middle line:84%
We get a huge storm
changes, migration.

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:44.630 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you talk about
the migrant problem,

00:07:44.630 --> 00:07:45.430 align:middle line:90%
it goes on and on.

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:48.700 align:middle line:84%
Nat Geo says five degrees is
the absolute worst condition.

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:50.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's look
at our next graph.

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:53.620 align:middle line:10%
>>VALONE: So as you
kind of look at the 2100

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:57.220 align:middle line:10%
deadline for this change of
temperature, all of a sudden

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:59.770 align:middle line:10%
now 10 years later, we
see the best climatologist

00:07:59.770 --> 00:08:02.110 align:middle line:10%
in the world,
Stanford University,

00:08:02.110 --> 00:08:06.580 align:middle line:10%
Carnegie Institute agreeing
with five degrees C by 2100.

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:08.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right, and
then our last one here.

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:11.560 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: And so what I also
was wondering, what happens

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:13.960 align:middle line:90%
past 2100, because guess what?

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:18.691 align:middle line:10%
We're pushing the CO2
level up to 500, 600, 700.

00:08:18.691 --> 00:08:20.190 align:middle line:10%
On the right side
of this graph, you

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:24.760 align:middle line:10%
see all the climate models
predicting 600 to 800 parts

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:26.320 align:middle line:10%
per million of just CO2.

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:27.430 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: That is high.

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:27.920 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Thank you.

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:28.542 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That is high.

00:08:28.542 --> 00:08:29.366 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: That's
nice of you to admit.

00:08:29.366 --> 00:08:30.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How it got
there we can debate.

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:31.730 align:middle line:90%
But that is high.

00:08:31.730 --> 00:08:34.690 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Guess what the
studies show in classrooms

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:37.720 align:middle line:84%
when you reach 1,000
parts per million of CO2?

00:08:37.720 --> 00:08:40.711 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What might it
have been like, Tom,

00:08:40.711 --> 00:08:41.980 align:middle line:90%
60 million years ago--

00:08:41.980 --> 00:08:42.280 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: 50.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:42.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --with the dinosaurs?

00:08:42.850 --> 00:08:44.141 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: 50 million years ago.

00:08:44.141 --> 00:08:47.280 align:middle line:84%
It turns out the Eocene Epoch
was 800 parts per million

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:48.080 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:49.090 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right,
what caused that?

00:08:49.090 --> 00:08:50.200 align:middle line:90%
We didn't have man.

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:51.430 align:middle line:90%
We didn't have machines.

00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:52.572 align:middle line:90%
We didn't have industry.

00:08:52.572 --> 00:08:53.530 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: That's right.

00:08:53.530 --> 00:08:55.720 align:middle line:84%
There was something
happening to the climate that

00:08:55.720 --> 00:08:57.790 align:middle line:90%
caused it to go way up in 800.

00:08:57.790 --> 00:09:00.400 align:middle line:84%
But what I'm interested
in is the temperature

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:04.152 align:middle line:84%
was also 15 degrees C
higher than the present.

00:09:04.152 --> 00:09:05.110 align:middle line:90%
We're not talking five.

00:09:05.110 --> 00:09:05.980 align:middle line:90%
We're talking 15.

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:06.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's huge.

00:09:06.910 --> 00:09:07.785 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:09:07.785 --> 00:09:08.936 align:middle line:90%
If we reach 800 by 2100--

00:09:08.936 --> 00:09:10.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What do you
think is happening now?

00:09:10.330 --> 00:09:12.038 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: --we're
going to be a hothouse.

00:09:12.038 --> 00:09:14.650 align:middle line:84%
And guess what the
Eocene Epoch had?

00:09:14.650 --> 00:09:16.480 align:middle line:90%
Alligators in the Arctic.

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:18.860 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are you saying
that this is an earth cycle?

00:09:18.860 --> 00:09:19.660 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: No.

00:09:19.660 --> 00:09:23.260 align:middle line:84%
I'm saying this is artificially
avoiding the next ice age that

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:25.000 align:middle line:90%
should be happening right now.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.920 align:middle line:84%
As you can see from
the first graph,

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:30.400 align:middle line:84%
the temperature is going
down, down, down and starting

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:31.570 align:middle line:90%
to go up a little bit.

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:34.360 align:middle line:84%
But the important thing is
we were actually at the point

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:37.450 align:middle line:84%
where it should have been
starting to decrease.

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:39.640 align:middle line:84%
And instead we've heated
up the atmosphere so

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:43.300 align:middle line:84%
tremendously with CO2
obviously, heat-trapping gas,

00:09:43.300 --> 00:09:45.920 align:middle line:84%
that we're avoiding the ice
age, which is good news.

00:09:45.920 --> 00:09:47.080 align:middle line:90%
But we're over-driving it.

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:50.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How do you recommend
we get that temperature

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:51.710 align:middle line:90%
level down?

00:09:51.710 --> 00:09:56.950 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: We have to invent and
rediscover CO2 sequestration.

00:09:56.950 --> 00:09:58.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What is that?

00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:00.790 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: There is a number of
technologies that our institute

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:04.310 align:middle line:84%
actually advocates every month
in our Future Energy eNews,

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:08.110 align:middle line:84%
which is free at our website,
Integrity-Research.org.

00:10:08.110 --> 00:10:12.880 align:middle line:84%
And you can basically see that
universities and scientists

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:18.310 align:middle line:84%
have already not only come up
with iron seeding of the oceans

00:10:18.310 --> 00:10:21.990 align:middle line:84%
to get plankton to absorb
millions of tons of CO2,

00:10:21.990 --> 00:10:27.080 align:middle line:84%
but there's also special types
of concrete that absorb CO2.

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:31.920 align:middle line:84%
There's types of technologies
that actually bury it

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:35.310 align:middle line:84%
in rock so that it's
actually reformed

00:10:35.310 --> 00:10:38.010 align:middle line:90%
into a concrete-type substance.

00:10:38.010 --> 00:10:41.580 align:middle line:84%
There's buildings, building
materials that absorb CO2.

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:45.510 align:middle line:84%
So we need all of that
into the billion ton range.

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:51.070 align:middle line:84%
And even director and
CEO of Virgin Galactic

00:10:51.070 --> 00:10:54.840 align:middle line:84%
was interested in offering
$10 million prize.

00:10:54.840 --> 00:10:57.230 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's not enough to
accomplish a billion ton--

00:10:57.230 --> 00:10:58.030 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No.

00:10:58.030 --> 00:10:59.250 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: --of sequestration.

00:10:59.250 --> 00:11:00.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's a start.

00:11:00.250 --> 00:11:01.980 align:middle line:90%
But it's not a lot.

00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:05.820 align:middle line:84%
What got you interested in
the possibility that humans

00:11:05.820 --> 00:11:07.410 align:middle line:90%
are contributing to this?

00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:11.920 align:middle line:84%
What did you see personally,
Tom, to make you feel that way?

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:15.030 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well,
actually the pollution

00:11:15.030 --> 00:11:19.230 align:middle line:84%
that fossil fuels cause
I felt was serious enough

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:21.590 align:middle line:90%
to be concerned about.

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:23.850 align:middle line:90%
I'm sensitive to air pollution.

00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:25.930 align:middle line:90%
Indoor air pollution bothers me.

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:28.650 align:middle line:84%
I used colloidal
silver nose sprays.

00:11:28.650 --> 00:11:32.195 align:middle line:84%
I use ozone generators
to sanitize the air.

00:11:32.195 --> 00:11:34.320 align:middle line:84%
Indoor air can be worse
than outdoor air sometimes.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:35.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Of course.

00:11:35.120 --> 00:11:36.090 align:middle line:90%
Of course.

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:38.010 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: But I also
was aware of the fact

00:11:38.010 --> 00:11:40.980 align:middle line:84%
that if you study
Carl Jung psychology,

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:45.720 align:middle line:84%
that the archetype of fossil
fuels is macabre and morbid.

00:11:45.720 --> 00:11:48.870 align:middle line:84%
You're dealing with
a dead symbol that

00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:50.700 align:middle line:90%
should remain in the ground.

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:53.100 align:middle line:84%
And instead we're
digging it up as if we're

00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:57.090 align:middle line:84%
some type of Halloween
type of figure

00:11:57.090 --> 00:12:02.070 align:middle line:84%
and trying to revivify it
to make it more energetic.

00:12:02.070 --> 00:12:09.030 align:middle line:84%
This is a whole misuse of
nature's and Gaia's resources.

00:12:09.030 --> 00:12:11.310 align:middle line:84%
Instead, the free
energy movement,

00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:15.150 align:middle line:84%
which is now
bearing fruit, shows

00:12:15.150 --> 00:12:17.790 align:middle line:84%
that there's energy available
from the quantum vacuum--

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:20.940 align:middle line:84%
clean, pure, light
type of energy

00:12:20.940 --> 00:12:24.510 align:middle line:84%
that is totally different
in symbolic form

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:26.724 align:middle line:84%
than the dead, morbid type
of energy we're using now.

00:12:26.724 --> 00:12:28.140 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well,
there's no question

00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:30.600 align:middle line:84%
that we should be using
different kinds of fuels

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:31.440 align:middle line:90%
on this planet.

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:33.205 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Do we even need fuel?

00:12:33.205 --> 00:12:34.080 align:middle line:90%
This is the question.

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:37.150 align:middle line:84%
And this has been our problem
from the past 100 years,

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:40.740 align:middle line:84%
thinking that fuel
was our only resource.

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:44.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, Nikola Tesla lectured
us very seriously about it.

00:12:44.850 --> 00:12:47.790 align:middle line:84%
If we continue to use
fuel as a resource,

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:50.280 align:middle line:84%
the coming generations
will actually suffer.

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:52.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Stanford University's
Doctor Mark Jacobson

00:12:52.740 --> 00:12:55.560 align:middle line:84%
talks about 139
countries that he

00:12:55.560 --> 00:13:00.520 align:middle line:84%
says by 2050 could be
using renewable systems.

00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:01.320 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:02.778 align:middle line:10%
>>MARK JACOBSON:
We think that it's

00:13:02.778 --> 00:13:05.760 align:middle line:10%
possible to address all of
global carbon and air pollution

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:08.160 align:middle line:10%
problems simultaneously
by transitioning

00:13:08.160 --> 00:13:12.570 align:middle line:10%
every single country and
state to 100% clean, renewable

00:13:12.570 --> 00:13:15.240 align:middle line:10%
energy, particularly wind,
water, and solar power.

00:13:15.240 --> 00:13:19.260 align:middle line:10%
We calculate 22 million new jobs
worldwide by such a transition.

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:22.740 align:middle line:10%
Onshore and offshore wind;
solar photovoltaics on rooftops

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:25.130 align:middle line:10%
and in power plants;
utility scale solar;

00:13:25.130 --> 00:13:27.270 align:middle line:10%
photovoltaics;
also utility scale

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:31.230 align:middle line:10%
concentrated solar power
and then geothermal power;

00:13:31.230 --> 00:13:34.470 align:middle line:10%
existing, not new
hydroelectric power;

00:13:34.470 --> 00:13:36.780 align:middle line:10%
and tiny amounts of
tidal wave power.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:38.820 align:middle line:10%
We find for each
country of the world

00:13:38.820 --> 00:13:42.270 align:middle line:10%
that we tested that
it's possible to power

00:13:42.270 --> 00:13:45.120 align:middle line:10%
each country entirely by
wind, water, and solar.

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:47.610 align:middle line:10%
Electricity is much more
efficient than burning things.

00:13:47.610 --> 00:13:50.190 align:middle line:84%
For example, take
a gasoline car.

00:13:50.190 --> 00:13:54.300 align:middle line:84%
Gasoline car, only 17% to 20%
of the energy in the gasoline

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:55.250 align:middle line:90%
goes to move the car.

00:13:55.250 --> 00:13:56.430 align:middle line:90%
And the rest is waste heat.

00:13:56.430 --> 00:13:59.100 align:middle line:10%
If you have an electric
car, of the electricity that

00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:02.215 align:middle line:10%
goes into the car in starting
batteries, 80% to 86%

00:14:02.215 --> 00:14:03.090 align:middle line:10%
goes to move the car.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:09.480 align:middle line:10%
So we reduce significantly
over 60%, 70% the energy

00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:11.140 align:middle line:10%
need in transportation.

00:14:11.140 --> 00:14:12.570 align:middle line:10%
When you average
over all sectors,

00:14:12.570 --> 00:14:15.750 align:middle line:10%
there is about a 32%
reduction in energy demand

00:14:15.750 --> 00:14:17.070 align:middle line:10%
due to this efficiency.

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:19.700 align:middle line:10%
And then we can squeeze
out another about 7%

00:14:19.700 --> 00:14:22.090 align:middle line:10%
in use energy efficiency
improvements beyond that.

00:14:22.090 --> 00:14:26.320 align:middle line:84%
So we get about 39% reduction of
power demand over all sectors.

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:28.320 align:middle line:10%
So the problem with wind
and solar, for example,

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:30.611 align:middle line:10%
is the wind doesn't always
blow, the sun doesn't shine.

00:14:30.611 --> 00:14:33.270 align:middle line:10%
So the concern has been that
the grid will be unstable.

00:14:33.270 --> 00:14:35.490 align:middle line:10%
You'll have high cost
to keep it stable

00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:38.390 align:middle line:10%
if we go to large-scale
wind, water, and solar power.

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:40.185 align:middle line:10%
But it turns out
this is not the case.

00:14:40.185 --> 00:14:41.310 align:middle line:10%
It's actually the opposite.

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:43.920 align:middle line:10%
>>AMORY LOVINS: In
2014, more than a fourth

00:14:43.920 --> 00:14:46.320 align:middle line:10%
of Germany's
electricity consumption

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:51.690 align:middle line:10%
was renewable and about half in
four other European countries

00:14:51.690 --> 00:14:54.840 align:middle line:10%
with modest or no hydropower.

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.560 align:middle line:10%
None of them added bulk storage.

00:14:56.560 --> 00:14:59.680 align:middle line:10%
All of them sustained high
reliability for Denmark

00:14:59.680 --> 00:15:02.490 align:middle line:10%
and Germany, about 10 times
better than America's.

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:04.680 align:middle line:84%
>>JACOBSON: The actual
demand is variable itself.

00:15:04.680 --> 00:15:07.290 align:middle line:10%
So baseload power doesn't
really mean anything,

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:10.620 align:middle line:10%
because you always, even
today and historically, you've

00:15:10.620 --> 00:15:13.330 align:middle line:10%
always needed some kind of
peaking to fill in the gap.

00:15:13.330 --> 00:15:15.930 align:middle line:84%
So like nuclear power,
which provides baseload,

00:15:15.930 --> 00:15:18.834 align:middle line:84%
does not help you actually
match power demand.

00:15:18.834 --> 00:15:20.250 align:middle line:84%
Coal, which is
primarily baseload,

00:15:20.250 --> 00:15:22.410 align:middle line:84%
does not help you
meet the peaks.

00:15:22.410 --> 00:15:26.220 align:middle line:10%
It just gives you some flat,
underlying amount of energy.

00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:29.850 align:middle line:10%
But we found that by
electrifying all sectors--

00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:33.190 align:middle line:10%
so that's transportation,
heating and cooling industry

00:15:33.190 --> 00:15:35.230 align:middle line:10%
in addition to electricity--

00:15:35.230 --> 00:15:37.320 align:middle line:10%
it actually makes it easier
to match power demand

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:39.930 align:middle line:10%
at a cost of about 10
and a half to 10.6 cents

00:15:39.930 --> 00:15:42.450 align:middle line:10%
per kilowatt hour, which
is similar to the energy

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:44.180 align:middle line:10%
cost of a fossil fuel system.

00:15:44.180 --> 00:15:44.980 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:46.390 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: So it can be done.

00:15:46.390 --> 00:15:46.670 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:15:46.670 --> 00:15:47.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It can be done.

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:49.340 align:middle line:90%
Well, why aren't we doing it?

00:15:49.340 --> 00:15:51.900 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well,
Mark Jacobson has

00:15:51.900 --> 00:15:53.760 align:middle line:84%
received a lot of
criticism, saying

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:55.410 align:middle line:90%
that it would be too expensive.

00:15:55.410 --> 00:15:58.710 align:middle line:84%
Various countries he's named
are actually resistant.

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:01.360 align:middle line:84%
Poland, for example,
is loving the fact

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:03.780 align:middle line:84%
they can get cheap
coal in their homes.

00:16:03.780 --> 00:16:05.800 align:middle line:84%
And the pollution,
they don't care about.

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:08.700 align:middle line:84%
So it's changing
mindset to even be

00:16:08.700 --> 00:16:11.672 align:middle line:84%
concerned about air pollution
and, of course, climate change.

00:16:11.672 --> 00:16:14.130 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I don't think I'd like
a coal furnace in my house.

00:16:14.130 --> 00:16:15.180 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: No, but
the Polish people--

00:16:15.180 --> 00:16:15.330 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Would you?

00:16:15.330 --> 00:16:16.759 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: --seem
to be used to it.

00:16:16.759 --> 00:16:18.300 align:middle line:84%
And there's many
other countries that

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:20.870 align:middle line:90%
burn very dirty types of fuel.

00:16:20.870 --> 00:16:24.010 align:middle line:84%
And of course, even
a solar converter,

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:27.040 align:middle line:84%
like in India and Africa, is
a wonderful new innovation

00:16:27.040 --> 00:16:27.840 align:middle line:90%
to them.

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:32.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When you started
thinking about free energy, how

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:32.840 align:middle line:90%
old were you?

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:34.940 align:middle line:90%
When did that start?

00:16:34.940 --> 00:16:36.844 align:middle line:90%
Were you a kid?

00:16:36.844 --> 00:16:37.760 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Pretty much.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:42.200 align:middle line:84%
I was actually in college
at the time, a grad student

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:47.180 align:middle line:84%
and in my 20s, looking for a
master's project that I felt,

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:49.790 align:middle line:84%
I want to do something that
I would be interested in

00:16:49.790 --> 00:16:52.470 align:middle line:84%
rather than wait for the
professor to tell me.

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:55.820 align:middle line:84%
In one case, I was
offered a PhD thesis

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:58.580 align:middle line:84%
on the distribution
of utility generators

00:16:58.580 --> 00:16:59.910 align:middle line:90%
throughout the country.

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:00.710 align:middle line:90%
Whoop-de-doos.

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:04.400 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to be able to talk
about my PhD thesis after that.

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:07.940 align:middle line:10%
So that's why I investigated
"Sunburst, Return

00:17:07.940 --> 00:17:09.714 align:middle line:10%
of the Ancients"
by Norman Paulsen.

00:17:09.714 --> 00:17:11.130 align:middle line:84%
And I went out to
their community.

00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:14.599 align:middle line:84%
You saw this, quote unquote,
"free energy generator,"

00:17:14.599 --> 00:17:16.910 align:middle line:84%
Bruce DePalma's device,
and thought, hey,

00:17:16.910 --> 00:17:19.430 align:middle line:84%
I may be able to test this
for a master's project.

00:17:19.430 --> 00:17:20.990 align:middle line:84%
And luckily I
convinced my professor

00:17:20.990 --> 00:17:22.740 align:middle line:84%
to let me do that for
a master in physics.

00:17:22.740 --> 00:17:24.281 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What are
your thoughts, Tom,

00:17:24.281 --> 00:17:26.839 align:middle line:84%
that every household would
have some kind of free energy

00:17:26.839 --> 00:17:28.216 align:middle line:90%
device attached to it?

00:17:28.216 --> 00:17:29.090 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:17:29.090 --> 00:17:30.506 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Not hooked
into the grid?

00:17:30.506 --> 00:17:31.910 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:35.660 align:middle line:84%
Having stand-alone power is the
only answer to climate change.

00:17:35.660 --> 00:17:42.140 align:middle line:84%
And really this is the kind of
self-sustaining type of future

00:17:42.140 --> 00:17:46.070 align:middle line:84%
that human race needs for all
the dangerous storms we've

00:17:46.070 --> 00:17:47.560 align:middle line:90%
been receiving.

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:51.590 align:middle line:84%
Just a few years ago, we
had 200 tornadoes in one day

00:17:51.590 --> 00:17:53.330 align:middle line:90%
throughout the Midwest.

00:17:53.330 --> 00:17:55.640 align:middle line:84%
Popular Science this month
actually shows the map

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:57.230 align:middle line:90%
of all those 200 tornadoes.

00:17:57.230 --> 00:17:58.470 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Power lines down.

00:17:58.470 --> 00:17:59.270 align:middle line:90%
It was a mess.

00:17:59.270 --> 00:17:59.990 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: You name it.

00:17:59.990 --> 00:18:00.740 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:02.531 align:middle line:84%
And of course hurricanes
are getting worse.

00:18:02.531 --> 00:18:04.419 align:middle line:90%
I mean, we don't need that.

00:18:04.419 --> 00:18:05.960 align:middle line:84%
But we're going to
be experiencing it

00:18:05.960 --> 00:18:07.520 align:middle line:90%
all throughout the century.

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:11.520 align:middle line:84%
Even each generation will
see worsening conditions.

00:18:11.520 --> 00:18:13.670 align:middle line:84%
So the first step
is Mark Jacobson

00:18:13.670 --> 00:18:17.780 align:middle line:84%
says to go ahead with
the clean energy first.

00:18:17.780 --> 00:18:21.210 align:middle line:84%
Renewable energy has to be a
mandate for all the countries,

00:18:21.210 --> 00:18:23.180 align:middle line:84%
including unfortunately
the carbon

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:28.310 align:middle line:84%
tax that was just voted
out of being instituted

00:18:28.310 --> 00:18:30.860 align:middle line:90%
in a Western state recently.

00:18:30.860 --> 00:18:32.810 align:middle line:84%
Eventually we'll
have to face facts

00:18:32.810 --> 00:18:36.950 align:middle line:84%
and say, yes, it's about time
we stopped emitting carbon.

00:18:36.950 --> 00:18:38.780 align:middle line:90%
Carbon dioxide is a pollutant.

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:41.390 align:middle line:84%
And we didn't ever
know, I don't think,

00:18:41.390 --> 00:18:44.400 align:middle line:84%
that the Earth was that
temperature sensitive to CO2

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:45.200 align:middle line:90%
levels.

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:46.783 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You and I
differ a little bit

00:18:46.783 --> 00:18:47.970 align:middle line:90%
on how we got to this point.

00:18:47.970 --> 00:18:48.770 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Yes.

00:18:48.770 --> 00:18:50.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But we agree
on certain things.

00:18:50.730 --> 00:18:53.557 align:middle line:84%
For example, I don't think we
should be polluting the planet.

00:18:53.557 --> 00:18:54.390 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Thank you.

00:18:54.390 --> 00:18:56.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And we're
doing that in a big way.

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:59.120 align:middle line:84%
I'm a believer in the
abiotic oil theory.

00:18:59.120 --> 00:19:02.720 align:middle line:84%
I don't think our oil is from
plants and dead dinosaurs.

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:06.740 align:middle line:84%
But I do believe that we
shouldn't be burning it

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:09.350 align:middle line:84%
and to get into a
different source.

00:19:09.350 --> 00:19:12.290 align:middle line:84%
So though we may disagree on
certain aspects of climate

00:19:12.290 --> 00:19:15.110 align:middle line:84%
change, we do agree
on the fact that we

00:19:15.110 --> 00:19:17.180 align:middle line:90%
need to do something about it.

00:19:17.180 --> 00:19:18.740 align:middle line:90%
And it's there.

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:20.780 align:middle line:84%
What would it cost to
have a device like that

00:19:20.780 --> 00:19:24.440 align:middle line:84%
attached to your house, to
have your own power system?

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:26.840 align:middle line:84%
>>VALONE: Well, the
cost is probably

00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:32.870 align:middle line:84%
something that's still in the
gray zone of possibilities.

00:19:32.870 --> 00:19:34.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Meaning it's
too high right now?

00:19:34.790 --> 00:19:35.660 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Yes, yes.

00:19:35.660 --> 00:19:37.970 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, I can equate
it to, for example,

00:19:37.970 --> 00:19:42.860 align:middle line:84%
the backup natural gas
generators that are available.

00:19:42.860 --> 00:19:46.730 align:middle line:84%
We have power outages even in
the Maryland area, Washington

00:19:46.730 --> 00:19:48.830 align:middle line:90%
DC area every so often.

00:19:48.830 --> 00:19:52.040 align:middle line:84%
And people often experience
that even with storms.

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:54.140 align:middle line:84%
You not only have the
damage from the hurricane,

00:19:54.140 --> 00:19:57.260 align:middle line:84%
but you also lose power
for any number of weeks.

00:19:57.260 --> 00:19:59.870 align:middle line:84%
So backup generators
are a solution,

00:19:59.870 --> 00:20:01.190 align:middle line:90%
running on natural gas.

00:20:01.190 --> 00:20:04.040 align:middle line:84%
But you'll spend at
least $10,000 or more

00:20:04.040 --> 00:20:07.220 align:middle line:84%
to get that type of
generator as a alternative.

00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:09.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That cost will
come down though, won't it,

00:20:09.410 --> 00:20:10.310 align:middle line:90%
dramatically?

00:20:10.310 --> 00:20:10.940 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Sure, and--

00:20:10.940 --> 00:20:13.398 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Or maybe it will be
$1,000 or something like that.

00:20:13.398 --> 00:20:15.200 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:16.670 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How would it work?

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:19.400 align:middle line:10%
>>VALONE: Well, what
we're now seeing finally--

00:20:19.400 --> 00:20:22.250 align:middle line:10%
and I'm looking at
almost 30 years later

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:25.100 align:middle line:10%
from when I started in 1980--

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:28.220 align:middle line:10%
to actually see the
first presentation

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:32.420 align:middle line:10%
that's very solid in terms
of the evidence behind it

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:34.745 align:middle line:10%
for the Arthur Manelas device.

00:20:34.745 --> 00:20:37.360 align:middle line:84%
And that was presented
by Brian Ahern, Dr. Brian

00:20:37.360 --> 00:20:40.940 align:middle line:84%
Ahern at our last conference
on future energy, the 10th one

00:20:40.940 --> 00:20:43.310 align:middle line:90%
we had during the summer.

00:20:43.310 --> 00:20:46.670 align:middle line:84%
FutureEnergy.org is our website
for all our consciences.

00:20:46.670 --> 00:20:51.650 align:middle line:10%
And what was surprising about
that is the Manelas device

00:20:51.650 --> 00:20:55.310 align:middle line:10%
works on strontium
ferrite billet,

00:20:55.310 --> 00:20:58.100 align:middle line:10%
nanocrystalline
strontium ferrite billet,

00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:01.000 align:middle line:10%
which has crystal sizes
less than 10 nanometers.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.150 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That small?

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:02.950 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Yes.

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:04.877 align:middle line:84%
And what Dr. Ahern
discovered, because he

00:21:04.877 --> 00:21:06.710 align:middle line:84%
worked in the cold
fusion area that's always

00:21:06.710 --> 00:21:09.680 align:middle line:84%
been a problematic area
to research-- he said,

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:12.510 align:middle line:84%
the only successful
cold fusion devices,

00:21:12.510 --> 00:21:16.910 align:middle line:84%
which is called LENR,
low-energy nuclear reactions,

00:21:16.910 --> 00:21:21.440 align:middle line:84%
is the 10 nanometer or
less palladium crystals,

00:21:21.440 --> 00:21:22.550 align:middle line:90%
for example.

00:21:22.550 --> 00:21:25.310 align:middle line:84%
And Arata was one
of the doctors who

00:21:25.310 --> 00:21:28.580 align:middle line:84%
were successful in getting
excess heat generation.

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:31.700 align:middle line:84%
Well, the Manelas device
produces excess electricity

00:21:31.700 --> 00:21:34.422 align:middle line:90%
even after 25 miles of running--

00:21:34.422 --> 00:21:35.630 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's a good thing.

00:21:35.630 --> 00:21:35.990 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: --several weeks.

00:21:35.990 --> 00:21:36.790 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:21:36.790 --> 00:21:39.740 align:middle line:84%
The voltage goes up on
the billet in the battery,

00:21:39.740 --> 00:21:43.010 align:middle line:84%
because the billet is inside
the battery, and it gets cooler.

00:21:43.010 --> 00:21:44.630 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Dr. Mark
Jacobson thinks

00:21:44.630 --> 00:21:47.056 align:middle line:84%
that we should be
doing all electricity.

00:21:47.056 --> 00:21:47.930 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Absolutely.

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:49.020 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is it doable?

00:21:49.020 --> 00:21:49.820 align:middle line:90%
>>VALONE: Yes.

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:53.750 align:middle line:84%
From what his research proves
and what other climatologists

00:21:53.750 --> 00:21:56.420 align:middle line:84%
and renewable
energy experts say,

00:21:56.420 --> 00:21:59.640 align:middle line:84%
we can be running on 100%
free renewable energy

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:00.440 align:middle line:90%
if we choose to.

00:22:00.440 --> 00:22:02.440 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Of course, the
genius about free energy

